Memory Management: Java manages memory automatically using JVM.
JVM - Java Virtual Machine


Stack Memory:
i)Follows LIFO ordering.
ii)Used for primitive data types and references.
iii)Fast Access.
iv)Memory is freed automatically when execution completes.
v)Used for local variables, method calls, function execution flow


Heap Memory:
i)Used for storing objects and instance variables.
ii)Shared across multiple threads.
iii)Slower than Stack memory.
iv)Managed by Garbage collector.


Garbage Collection: It is process by which Java deletes all unused
objects from the memory.

Student s=new Student();
s=null;


Heap ->  

Young Gen -> Eden Space, Survivor S0(From), Survivor S1(From)
Old Gen(Tenured)
Metaspace 

Young Gen : All new objects are created.

Eden Space: Object birthplace
Survivor Space: These are used to track surviving objects.



Old Gen(Tenured): Stores long lived objects like cached data, session data
singleton object. Garbage collection is very less frequent.

Metaspace: stores class metadata, method info, static variables 




Enum: It is a special data type for fixed set of constants.

final int a=10;

enum status{
  
  ON, OFF, PENDING
}

enum days{
  
  SUNDAY, MONDAY, TUESDAY, WEDNESDAY, THURSDAY, FRIDAY, SATARDAY
}



i)It is used to represent a group of related constants.
ii)Improves code readability.
iii)Provides type safety.

